issue.title: feat: add rateLimiting and cooldown support
issue.body:
Adds a generic cooldown and rateLimiting interface.
Almost anything can be customized, except for when the things are called (befor, or after checks ect, this is currently at an opinionated point which I think should be fine but I didn't see a solution).

Provided are CooldownType, RateLimitType | these interfaces should implement the storing and retrieving of the cooldown/ratelimit state of entities, the default provided impl is a local cache using hashmaps (this is ofcourse insufficient for long cooldowns, ratelimits that should persist over restarts or in multiprocess environments).

RateLimiter and CooldownHandler interfaces which contain the central logic.

RateLimitProvider and CooldownProvider which fetch certain configurable values or can be used to just provide centralized configuration of ratelimits/cooldowns (maybe you want to store global stuff in a db idk).

Cooldowns are stored as epochMillis and passed as kotlin.time.Duration 
Ratelimits are stored using classes implementing UsageHistory interface (UsageHistory also stores the moments cooldowns were hit).

Progressive cooldowns are cooldowns you can increment during the execution of a command, these values are stored inside the commandContext.
Command cooldowns are just command specific cooldowns applied only when that command is ran.
Global cooldowns are applied for all commands (you can still put if checks and such ofc).

Any feedback is welcome, this is my first big pr to the project <3
All detekt stuff passes atm.
Still untested, but I wanted to share the design and gather feedback at this point.

comment.body:
I'm interesting in picking this up, but I'm having a not so easy time understanding this previous work.  
Some more meta documentation would be nice to have.

What's the real distinction between cooldown and rate limit? Isn't a cooldown a specific case of rate limiting? As in, it is the same as 1 event per time period?

In any case, I think we should have a discussion (on #27 or on a new issue) about what kind of API and behaviour we're looking for. This would help direct my attention on what to implement and how.

issue.title: index-backup-restore: 0 doc in target index
issue.body:
**Overview of the Issue**
When uploading documents to the target index, the following error appears in VSCode:

          Error: Response status code does not indicate success: 400 (Bad Request).
          Waiting 10 seconds for target to index content...
          NOTE: For really large indexes it may take longer to index all content.

          SAFEGUARD CHECK: Source and target index counts should match
          Source index contains 353 docs
          Target index contains 0 docs

In the Azure activity logs, "List changes of a single resource" is marked as successful. No step is indicated as failed.
